  "prompt": "In what medium does light (photon) travel?",
  "response": "Light (photons) can travel through various media:\n\n1. Vacuum\n- Fastest speed (approximately 299,792,458 meters per second)\n- No particles or matter present\n- Electromagnetic waves can propagate without a physical medium\n\n2. Air\n- Slightly slower than in vacuum\n- Sparse molecules slightly affect light speed\n\n3. Transparent materials\n- Glass\n- Water\n- Transparent plastics\n- Crystal\n- Each material has a different refractive index affecting light speed\n\n4. Space\n- Photons can travel through empty space between celestial bodies\n- No medium is required for propagation\n\nThe key point is that unlike sound waves, which require a physical medium to propagate, light can travel through vacuum and does not need a material medium to move.\n\nElectromagnetic waves, including light, are self-propagating waves of electric and magnetic fields that can travel through space without requiring a physical medium for transmission.",
